  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article critiques the rigid application of the *Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)* by developers who prioritize minimalism over cohesion, leading to fragmented, hard-to-maintain codebases. It argues that while SRP promotes modularity and clarity, treating \"small\" as synonymous with \"cohesive\" (e.g., splitting functions into single-line files or overusing technical roles like hooks/reducers in React/Redux) creates organizational debt, dependency chaos, and brittle tests. Using metaphors like \"Unix philosophy\" (emphasizing composition over atomic decomposition) and \"MC Escher Pattern\" (infinite, disorienting abstraction), the author advocates for pragmatic SRP: grouping logically related code that changes together, rather than enforcing arbitrary boundaries. The tone is analytical and cautionary, targeting software architects and developers who risk sacrificing productivity for ideological purity. Key technologies discussed include React/Redux ecosystems, where excessive SRP can exacerbate complexity.",
